observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) sustain the optimum utilization of the LGU’s 20% DF in consonance with Section 287 of R.A. 7160 and DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Circular No. 1; 

(b) instruct the Local Development Council to identify priority projects which are urgent as early as possible to ensure the swift delivery of benefits to the intended beneficiaries without delay; 

(c) require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), Head, BAC Secretariat and Technical Working Group to work on the completion of the documentary deficiencies and submit the same to the Audit Team; and 

(d) instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the required documents for each type of transaction are submitted/attached to the disbursement vouchers before the processing and payments.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive Agreed to:
instruct the Local Development Council (LDC) to
identify stakeholders by key planning and development sectors or coverage;
prepare an action plan for approaching and involving each person or group;
develop and implement an Information and Education Campaign (IEC) plan to inform and solicit support and commitment of the identified stakeholders and the general public;
involve the general community by conducting focus group discussions, interviews, surveys, and other innovative forms of indirect participation in case there are still not enough information to create a comprehensive plans and programs; and
require the Punong Barangays within the Municipality to submit their respective Barangay Development Plan (BDP) to be incorporated in the preparation of updated CLUP and CDP.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Council to:
prepare the request for an appropriation ordinance for the utilization of unexpended LDRRM Fund once the resolution for the adoption of the amended LDRRMFIP was approved;
conduct adequate research and planning prior to the preparation of LDRRMFIP;
use Program of Works and project proposals with estimate of expenses as basis for the proposed budget of each PPA to be included in the LDRRMFIP;
set a realistic and specific schedule of implementation for each PPA to ensure the timely enjoyment of benefits therefrom by the community; and
submit the budget proposals in accordance with the schedule for budget preparation to have an ample time for review and revision.

8.28.   We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
instruct the Market Committee:
to evaluate the provision in the Market Code limiting stallholders to lease a maximum of two stalls. They should assess its relevance in the current market context. If deemed still pertinent, efforts should be made to ensure strict adherence to this provision. Otherwise, update the specific provision in the Market Code;
re-assess the space occupied by each stall and categorize them accurately to ensure a more precise computation of rental fees;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
strictly implement the current rental rates as specified in the Market Code;
follow the mode and frequency of collection of market rentals stated in Section 1, Chapter III of the Market Code, where issuance of Official Receipt is employed;
conduct investigation and promptly revoke the rent of the stallholders who are found to be subleasing their stalls to third parties; and
immediately revoke the rental agreement for the abandoned stalls and implement procedures for vacated stalls.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE)

(a) reassess its existing organizational structure to upgrade the plantilla of personnel requirement for possible budgeting, thereby, avoiding the hiring of excessive number of job-order personnel; 

(b) instruct the Municipal Human Resources Management Officer (MHRMO) to observe prudence and diligence on determining the necessity and propriety of hiring of job orders.

We recommended that the Management 

(a) continue to comply with the GSIS, PhilHealth and Pag-IBIG regulations on the withholding and remittance of employees’ and employer contributions and loan amortizations of employees to the respective agencies to assure the enjoyment of all its members of social security benefits due them; 

(b) instruct the Accountant to strengthen her review function and institute regular reconciliation of the accounts to prevent errors such as negative abnormal account balances.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Agriculturist to find ways to locate contracts and other reports pertaining to the procured goats in CY 2000 to CY 2005.  

Henceforth (a) conduct physical count to validate existence; 

(b) prepare various records and reports such as BAPC and RPCBA for submission to Accounting Unit to take up the necessary adjustment in the books, if needed.

We recommended that (a)  Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO), the Health Officer and other concerned municipal officials to immediately coordinate with the barangay officials concerned for the strict implementation of the Municipality of Talavera Solid Waste Management Ordinance of 2007, particularly in the prohibition on the littering, dumping and open burning  of solid waste like plastic, dried leaves and other farm wastes; 
b) Municipal Agriculturist  encourage farmers to do composting of farm waste to enrich the soil with natural fertilizers; 
c) Municipal  Environment officer together with the Municipal Health Officer conduct proper information dissemination like conducting seminars, production of posters/ tarpaulins on the harmful effects to the health of the public of smoke from burning of solid waste.
